    <!-- Cyberbullying Section -->
    <section id="cyberbullying" class="py-16 bg-base-200">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center text-accent mb-12">Cyberbullying Prevention & Response</h2>
          
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
            <!-- What is Cyberbullying -->
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body space-y-6">
                <h3 class="card-title text-xl text-accent mb-4">What is Cyberbullying?</h3>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70 mb-4">
                  Cyberbullying is willful, repeated harm carried out through digital devices—phones, tablets, computers, game consoles, even smart-TV chat apps—by sending, posting, or sharing negative, false, or private content about someone else<Cite id="stopbullying2024" />.
                </p>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70 mb-6">
                  Unlike traditional face-to-face bullying, these attacks can follow a child 24/7, reach a vast audience in seconds, and leave a permanent record online, making them harder to escape and potentially more damaging to mental health<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /><Cite id="vogels2022" />.
                </p>

                <div class="mb-4 border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Common Forms</h4>
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
                    <li>Harassment &amp; flaming – repeated insults, threats, or humiliating comments in texts, DMs, or comment threads<Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                    <li>Exclusion – deliberately leaving someone out of group chats, games, or online communities<Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                    <li>Outing / doxxing – posting private messages, photos, or personal details to embarrass or endanger someone<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /><Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                    <li>Impersonation – creating fake profiles or hijacking accounts to spread rumors or pose as the victim<Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                    <li>Rumor-spreading &amp; image-based abuse – sharing edited or humiliating pictures, videos, or gossip<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="mb-4 border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Where It Happens Most</h4>
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
                    <li>Social media platforms (Snapchat, Instagram, TikTok, Facebook)<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /></li>
                    <li>Group texts and direct-message apps</li>
                    <li>Online multiplayer games and voice-chat services<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /></li>
                    <li>School learning portals, forums, or live-stream comments<Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold mb-2">Why It Can Be More Harmful Than In-Person Bullying</h4>
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
                    <li>Round-the-clock reach: messages arrive any time, even at home or during the night<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /></li>
                    <li>Amplified audience &amp; permanence: posts can be screenshotted, forwarded, and remain searchable long after deletion<Cite id="stopbullying2024" /></li>
                    <li>Anonymity: perpetrators may hide their identity, lowering empathy and increasing cruelty<Cite id="cyberbullyingrc2024" /></li>
                    <li>Growing prevalence: 59&nbsp;% of U.S. teens say they’ve been bullied or harassed online, and girls 15–17 report the highest rates<Cite id="vogels2022" />; 22&nbsp;% of bullied students (ages 12–18) said it happened online or by text in the 2021-22 school year<Cite id="nces2023" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Warning Signs -->
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body space-y-6">
                <h3 class="card-title text-xl text-accent mb-4">Warning Signs</h3>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70">
                  Children rarely tell adults outright when cyberbullying is happening. Watch for these behavioral and emotional red-flags — especially if several appear together:
                </p>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
                    <li>Noticeable shifts in device use — late-night scrolling, compulsive checking, or suddenly avoiding screens<Cite id="stopbullyingSigns2021" /></li>
                    <li>Strong emotional reactions after going online — visible laughter, anger, or tears immediately after reading messages<Cite id="stopbullyingSigns2021" /></li>
                    <li>Secrecy about digital life — quickly closing tabs, hiding the screen, or refusing to talk about online activities<Cite id="stopbullyingSigns2021" /></li>
                    <li>Withdrawal from friends or activities once enjoyed — skipping hang-outs, sports, or clubs; spending more time alone<Cite id="stopbullyingSigns2021" /><Cite id="netsmartz2025" /></li>
                    <li>Changes in sleep, appetite, or mood — headaches, stomach-aches, insomnia, overeating/undereating, signs of depression or anxiety<Cite id="netsmartz2025" /></li>
                    <li>Academic struggles or declining grades — trouble concentrating, sudden drop in performance<Cite id="netsmartz2025" /><Cite id="aapHealthyChildren2022" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70">
                  Any one sign doesn’t prove cyberbullying, but a pattern should prompt calm, open-ended questions and supportive follow-up.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Prevention Strategies -->
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body space-y-6">
                <h3 class="card-title text-xl text-accent mb-4">Prevention Strategies</h3>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70">
                  Strong relationships and smart tech settings are the best defense. Try weaving these practices into everyday life:
                </p>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1">
                    <li>Talk early &amp; often — ask what they’re doing online, how posts make them feel, and listen without judgment<Cite id="stopbullyingPrevent2024" /></li>
                    <li>Build a Family Media Plan — together set screen-time limits, approved apps, and agreed-upon consequences for hurtful posts<Cite id="aapHealthyChildren2022" /></li>
                    <li>Teach digital citizenship &amp; empathy — use school or free curricula (e.g., Common Sense) to practice respectful commenting, verifying sources, and protecting privacy<Cite id="aapCoE2024" /></li>
                    <li>Lock down privacy &amp; security tools — review every platform’s settings, enable two-factor log-ins, and show kids how to block/report harassers<Cite id="stopbullyingPrevent2024" /></li>
                    <li>Model healthy tech habits — put your own phone away at dinner, avoid posting gossip, and show how to pause before sharing<Cite id="aapHealthyChildren2022" /></li>
                    <li>Coach “up-stander” skills — encourage kids to support peers, refuse to forward cruel content, and speak up when someone’s targeted<Cite id="verywell2020" /></li>
                    <li>Document &amp; report problems fast — screenshot abusive messages, save dates/times, and follow school or platform reporting channels<Cite id="stopbullyingPrevent2024" /></li>
                    <li>Work with schools &amp; community — align household rules with classroom policies and community programs so messages stay consistent<Cite id="stopbullyingPrevent2024" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Response Actions -->
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mt-8">
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body space-y-6">
                <h3 class="card-title text-xl text-accent mb-4">If Your Child is Being Bullied</h3>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70">Stay calm and walk through these steps together—each one helps protect your child and limits further harm.</p>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <ul class="space-y-3">
                    <li><strong>Listen &amp; reassure.</strong> Thank your child for telling you, stay composed, and remind them the bullying is not their fault<Cite id="stopbullyingResponse2021" /> <Cite id="aapBullied2022" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Collect proof.</strong> Save screenshots, messages, dates, and usernames; keep a written log in case repeated incidents need to be shown to school officials or police<Cite id="stopbullyingResponse2021" /> <Cite id="cyberbullyingRC2024v2" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Block &amp; report online.</strong> Use the platform’s tools to block the bully, tighten privacy settings, and submit an official report<Cite id="stopbullyingResponse2021" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Notify the school.</strong> Share evidence with teachers or the principal and ask how they’ll enforce the district’s bullying policy<Cite id="stopbullyingResponse2021" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Don’t take the device away.</strong> Removing phones can feel like punishment and may discourage future disclosure; instead, agree on safety rules together<Cite id="aapBullied2022" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Offer emotional &amp; mental-health support.</strong> Check for changes in mood or sleep, encourage healthy routines, and consider a counselor, pediatrician, or calling 988 if distress escalates<Cite id="aapBullied2022" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Escalate when necessary.</strong> Contact law enforcement if there are threats, sexual images, or hate crimes, or if harassment continues after reporting<Cite id="stopbullyingResponse2021" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Follow up &amp; celebrate progress.</strong> Keep the conversation going, review reporting outcomes, and praise your child’s resilience and positive online choices<Cite id="aapBullied2022" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body space-y-6">
                <h3 class="card-title text-xl text-accent mb-4">If Your Child is Bullying Others</h3>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70">A calm, solution-focused response helps kids change harmful behavior without shame. Walk through these steps together:</p>

                <div class="border-l-4 border-accent/30 pl-4">
                  <ul class="space-y-3">
                    <li><strong>Start with an honest talk.</strong> Describe the exact behavior you saw or that was reported, emphasize that it is bullying, and listen for underlying motives (fitting-in, stress, past victimization, etc.)<Cite id="stopbullyingChildBully2024" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Make expectations crystal-clear.</strong> State that bullying will not be tolerated at home, school, or online; outline firm, consistent consequences such as loss of device time or activities<Cite id="stopbullyingChildBully2024" /> <Cite id="aapChildBully2024" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Build empathy &amp; accountability.</strong> Ask your child to imagine how the target feels; role-play respectful alternatives and require genuine apologies or restitution (e.g., repairing a post, writing a note)<Cite id="aapChildBully2024" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Address root causes.</strong> If bullying masks anxiety, trauma, or peer-pressure, involve the pediatrician, school counselor, or a mental-health professional; channel energy into positive groups, sports, or clubs<Cite id="stopbullyingChildBully2024" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Partner with the school.</strong> Work with teachers or principals on a behavior plan that includes monitoring, logical consequences, and opportunities for your child to make amends<Cite id="stopbullyingChildBully2024" /> <Cite id="aapChildBully2024" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Model &amp; monitor digital citizenship.</strong> Show respectful online behavior yourself, review privacy settings together, and keep an eye on accounts to reinforce progress without constant surveillance<Cite id="cyberbullyingBully2023" /></li>
                    <li><strong>Reinforce the positives.</strong> Praise every step toward kindness—helping a peer, posting something supportive, or handling conflict respectfully—to replace negativity with pro-social habits<Cite id="aapChildBully2024" /> <Cite id="cyberbullyingBully2023" /></li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/cyberbullying-infographic.pdf" download class="inline-flex items-center px-4 py-2 bg-primary text-primary-content rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-focus transition-colors">
          Need a one-page cheat sheet? Download our <span class="font-semibold mx-1">Cyberbullying Prevention &amp; Response infographic</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Device Safety Settings -->
    <section id="device-settings" class="py-16">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center text-primary mb-12">Device Safety Settings for Families</h2>
          
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
            <!-- iOS Settings -->
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body">
                <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                  <svg class="w-8 h-8 text-primary mr-3" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path d="M18.71 19.5c-.83 1.24-1.71 2.45-3.05 2.47-1.34.03-1.77-.79-3.29-.79-1.53 0-2 .77-3.27.82-1.31.05-2.3-1.32-3.14-2.53C4.25 17 2.94 12.45 4.7 9.39c.87-1.52 2.43-2.48 4.12-2.51 1.28-.02 2.5.87 3.29.87.78 0 2.26-1.07 3.81-.91.65.03 2.47.26 3.64 1.98-.09.06-2.17 1.28-2.15 3.81.03 3.02 2.65 4.03 2.68 4.04-.03.07-.42 1.44-1.38 2.83M13 3.5c.73-.83 1.94-1.46 2.94-1.5.13 1.17-.34 2.35-1.04 3.19-.69.85-1.83 1.51-2.95 1.42-.15-1.15.41-2.35 1.05-3.11z"/>
                  </svg>
                  <h3 class="card-title">iOS Parental Controls</h3>
                </div>
                <div class="prose text-base-content mb-4">
                  <h4 class="font-semibold">iOS 17 Setup Guide</h4>
                  <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-2">
                    <li><strong>Add child to Family&nbsp;Sharing.</strong> On the parent iPhone open <em>Settings › Family</em> › <em>Add Member</em> (or choose the child) and follow the prompts.</li>
                    <li><strong>Turn on Screen Time & set a passcode.</strong> Go to <em>Settings › Screen Time › [child]</em>, tap <em>Turn On Screen Time</em>, choose “This is My Child’s iPhone,” then create a 4-digit Screen Time passcode that’s different from the device unlock code.</li>
                    <li><strong>Schedule Downtime.</strong> In Screen Time tap <em>Downtime › Scheduled</em>, pick a start/end time (e.g., 9 PM–7 AM) and enable <em>Block at Downtime</em>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Set App Limits.</strong> Screen Time › <em>App Limits › Add Limit</em>, select categories/apps, set a daily limit (e.g., 1 hour) and tap <em>Add</em>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Configure Communication Limits.</strong> Screen Time › <em>Communication Limits</em>, decide who the child can contact during allowed time and downtime (e.g., Contacts Only).</li>
                    <li><strong>Choose “Always Allowed” apps.</strong> Screen Time › <em>Always Allowed</em>, keep essentials (Phone, Messages) and remove browsers/games you don’t want accessible 24/7.</li>
                    <li><strong>Turn on Content & Privacy Restrictions.</strong> Screen Time › <em>Content & Privacy Restrictions</em> → On, then adjust:
                      <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
                        <li><em>Web Content</em> → Limit Adult Websites</li>
                        <li><em>App Store Purchases</em> → In-App Purchases = Don’t Allow</li>
                        <li><em>Allowed Apps</em> → Hide Safari or Mail if desired</li>
                      </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Enable “Ask to Buy” & block in-app purchases.</strong> <em>Settings › Family › [child] › Ask to Buy</em> → Require Purchase Approval. Also ensure <em>In-App Purchases = Don’t Allow</em> (Content & Privacy › App Store Purchases).</li>
                    <li><strong>Turn on Communication Safety & Screen Distance.</strong> Screen Time › <em>Communication Safety</em> → On (nudity warnings); on supported models enable <em>Screen Distance</em> to remind kids not to hold the phone too close.</li>
                  </ol>
                </div>
                <div class="card-actions">
                  <a href="https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT208982" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">Official Apple Guide</a>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Android Settings -->
            <div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-lg">
              <div class="card-body">
                <div class="flex items-center mb-4">
                  <svg class="w-8 h-8 text-primary mr-3" fill="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path d="M17.523 15.3414c-.5511 0-.9993-.4486-.9993-.9997s.4482-.9993.9993-.9993c.5511 0 .9993.4483.9993.9993 0 .5511-.4482.9997-.9993.9997m-11.046 0c-.5511 0-.9993-.4486-.9993-.9997s.4482-.9993.9993-.9993c.5511 0 .9993.4483.9993.9993 0 .5511-.4482.9997-.9993.9997m11.4045-6.02l1.9973-3.4592a.416.416 0 00-.1567-.5703.416.416 0 00-.5703.1567l-2.0223 3.5014c-1.0048-.4745-2.1349-.7461-3.3508-.7461s-2.3459.2716-3.3507.7461L9.2434 5.8592a.4162.4162 0 00-.5703-.1567.416.416 0 00-.1567.5703l1.9973 3.4592C8.2558 10.5866 6.8147 12.6456 6.8147 15.0092H17.185c0-2.3636-1.441-4.4226-3.7035-5.6678"/>
                  </svg>
                  <h3 class="card-title">Android Controls</h3>
                </div>
                <p class="text-base-content opacity-70 mb-4">
                  > **PACIFIC UNIVERSITY TEAM:** Guide for Google Family Link and built-in Android parental controls
                </p>
                <div class="card-actions">
